Patch Set 2: Code-Review-2

A) We're currently on feature freeze
B) Is there any reason why we should not enable and configure this in the -paste.ini like every other middleware we use?
c) Is there any reason why we should not just document it and leave the above to deployer's discrete choice to add to the pipline?

Patch Set 2:

You can use it via Paste.ini, however as the author of the middleware I don't recommend it.

The first is configuration. The oslo way of configuration means keeping all options in one place, which makes it easier to manage and generate sample configs for. 

The second is consistency. By doing it this way, glance would be joining  Sahara, Ironic, and Keystone on using this particular method, and configuration will be consistent with any additional ones that are added (at this moment, nobody does it via paste.ini).

The third reason is performance. using it via paste only allows you to configure one single domain per paste filter invocation, meaning that adding more than one will add additional (though trivial) API overhead.

The fourth is configuration inheritance (feature): The middleware allows you to set one set of basic configuration options, and then selectively override them based on additional domains.

The fourth is latent configuration. In order to avoid having to document every custom header that must be added in order to make glance usable, you can instead add those manually to the shipped code. This creates a simple story where the configuration for glance "just works" for an operator, without having to dig into any additional documentation to figure out which headers Glance actually uses.

Patch Set 2:

And by fourth, I mean fifth. Doh!

Patch Set 2:

We already configure our middlewares in the -paste.ini (osprofiler, healthcheck).

Secondly this is not consistent with any other middleware we use.

For point three, there is perhaps room for improvement in the middleware then to allow better configurability via -paste.ini. ;)

Fifth point is fair enough why not c.

Patch Set 2:

My argument of consistency is from the context of OpenStack as a whole, and of Glance as a part of OpenStack. It is avery significant improvement in usability if the way you configure common features is consistent across all services in the integrated-release group. With that in mind, Glance's method of configuring middleware via paste.ini is actually inconsistent with the of openstack, and is the special snowflake. However, fixing that is outside the scope of this review.

Also, you did not truly address my comment on required parameters. If the custom http headers used by Glance are not set ("X-Custom-Header"), then the CORS contract is null and void and thus the feature will simply not work. Then, when an operator looks for documentation (even if they find the paste.ini version), and enables it, the CORS contract will still not work, until they dig into the http logs themselves and find the list of headers that Glance requires to operate. In short: Your suggestion creates two barriers for usage of a feature which should "just work", one of which is a non-intuitive problem that must be debugged by an operator, simply for the sake of architectural purity. My approach, on the other hand, "just works".

I welcome any additional changes to oslo.middleware that improve CORS configurability. Please add me to any reviews you put up so I can keep abreast of them. Lastly, with mitaka development now open for Glance, please remove the -2.

I think this sort of addition makes sense overall. It's not orthogonal to any of the features that exists and the configuration discussion only makes me think that the best way for us is to moved towards what other OS services are doing.

Patch Set 6:

A few things:

1- This doesn't actually work. I've written some tests ( http://paste.openstack.org/show/477858/ ), in addition to changes to the pastefile in __init__.py (not included in paste), however the response continues to return without any kind of CORS headers.

2- It appears that glance does not follow the standard config-file naming convention put forward by oslo. This creates some difficulties in paste.ini, because we'll have to either add a filter for each config file, or we'll have to document the customization of the paste.ini sufficiently to explain to operators how to make it all work. I don't like either of these options, as they are both workarounds for "Glance doesn't do things the way every other service in openstack does".

3- A fix for Timur's comments about X-Auth-Token has been proposed against oslo middleware here -> https://review.openstack.org/#/c/240984/ , his original patch has been reverted.

Patch Set 9:

Confirm that the change works for me. To make it devstack Glance's CORS fully functional I had to add the following lines to /etc/glance/glance-api.conf (besides overwriting /etc/glance/glance-api-paste.ini):

allowed_origin = http://localhost:8000
allow_headers = Content-Type,Cache-Control,Content-Language,Expires,Last-Modified,Pragma,X-Auth-Token

Is modifying allow_headers parameter a thing that should be left to deployer (as well as modifying allowed_origin, which truly cannot be known in advance)?

Patch Set 10:

@Timur- no, I don't think we should leave it to the operator. In fact, the paste file really should contain all headers that are required by the application, including things like version negotiation and more. Unfortunately I don't know glance well enough to go through the entire middleware chain and figure out which are needed, so I've updated the patch with an example allowed_headers. For the response, of course, the exposed headers will also have to be listed - could either you or Kairat do a quick check to see which other ones are missing?
